  "prompt": "Can cataracts affect younger people? What are the most common causes of it?",
  "response": "Yes, cataracts can affect younger people, although they are more commonly associated with aging. Cataracts occur when the lens of the eye becomes cloudy, leading to blurred vision and, if untreated, potential vision loss. In younger individuals, cataracts can develop due to various factors, some of which differ from those typically seen in older adults.\n\n### Most Common Causes of Cataracts in Younger People:\n1. **Congenital Cataracts**:\n   - Babies can be born with cataracts (congenital cataracts) or develop them in early childhood. These may be due to genetic factors, maternal infections during pregnancy (e.g., rubella, toxoplasmosis), or metabolic disorders.\n\n2. **Trauma**:\n   - Eye injuries, such as blunt trauma, penetrating wounds, or exposure to chemicals, can disrupt the lens and lead to cataract formation.\n\n3. **Medical Conditions**:\n   - Systemic diseases like diabetes, hypothyroidism, or certain genetic disorders (e.g., Down syndrome, Marfan syndrome) can increase the risk of cataracts in younger individuals.\n\n4. **Medications**:\n   - Long-term use of corticosteroids or other medications can contribute to cataract development.\n\n5. **Radiation Exposure**:\n   - Exposure to ultraviolet (UV) light, X-rays, or other forms of radiation can damage the lens and lead to cataracts.\n\n6. **Lifestyle Factors**:\n   - Smoking, excessive alcohol consumption, and poor nutrition have been linked to an increased risk of cataracts, even in younger people.\n\n7. **Eye Conditions**:\n   - Conditions like uveitis (inflammation of the eye) or prior eye surgeries can accelerate cataract formation.\n\n### Symptoms of Cataracts in Younger People:\n- Blurred or cloudy vision\n- Glare or halos around lights\n- Difficulty seeing at night\n- Fading or yellowing of colors\n- Frequent changes in eyeglass or contact lens prescription\n\n### Treatment:\nCataracts are treatable with surgery, which involves removing the cloudy lens and replacing it with an artificial intraocular lens (IOL). Early detection and intervention are crucial, especially in children, to prevent long-term vision problems.\n\nIf you suspect you or someone else may have cataracts, it\u2019s important to consult an eye care professional for a comprehensive evaluation and appropriate management.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
